00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:29.770
So, let's see.

00:05:29.770 --> 00:05:35.970
In this problem I think
I picked free conditions.

00:05:35.970 --> 00:05:40.210
So I made the interval minus
pi to pi, that's a change.

00:05:40.210 --> 00:05:43.690
Minus pi to pi just so we
have nice Fourier series.

00:05:43.690 --> 00:05:54.140
And here I have this boundary
is free, du/dx, u', at x=-pi,

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:59.160
for all time, so up
this line, is zero.

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:05.830
And also u' at plus pi,
and all time is zero.

00:06:05.830 --> 00:06:09.810
So up those lines,
heat's going out.

00:06:09.810 --> 00:06:11.110
That's what that means.

00:06:11.110 --> 00:06:14.940
Is that what that means, or does
that mean heat can't go out?

00:06:14.940 --> 00:06:18.050
No, so what's happening?

00:06:18.050 --> 00:06:19.370
Heat's not going out.

00:06:19.370 --> 00:06:21.640
Is that right?

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:23.460
The slope is zero, right?

00:06:23.460 --> 00:06:25.812
The slope is the
temperature gradient,

00:06:25.812 --> 00:06:27.520
we're requiring the
temperature gradient.

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:30.580
So the ends of the
bar are insulated.

00:06:30.580 --> 00:06:32.390
So this is insulated.

00:06:32.390 --> 00:06:35.790
No passage through, right?

00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:36.940
Is that what that means?

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:37.780
Yeah.

00:06:37.780 --> 00:06:43.300
It's like there's nobody,
it's cut off there.

00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:46.170
The rod isn't extended
for heat to go further.

00:06:46.170 --> 00:06:55.160
OK, so that tells us
what the x and the t,

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:57.230
what the A(x) and B(t) are.

00:06:57.230 --> 00:06:58.810
So here's the point.

00:06:58.810 --> 00:07:04.000
You plug that hoped-for solution
into the equation, right?

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:07.210
So I plug it in here.

00:07:07.210 --> 00:07:10.310
What do I have on the left
side, just the time derivative?

00:07:10.310 --> 00:07:16.260
So that's A times-- A(x)
B'(t), you see taking the time

00:07:16.260 --> 00:07:18.900
derivative doesn't touch A(x).

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:22.130
On the right-hand side,
I don't touch B(t),

00:07:22.130 --> 00:07:27.970
but I have a second
derivative of the x part.

00:07:27.970 --> 00:07:30.470
So far, so good.

00:07:30.470 --> 00:07:35.090
Now, a little trick.

00:07:35.090 --> 00:07:39.080
If I divide both
sides by A and by B,

00:07:39.080 --> 00:07:48.250
I get B'/B equaling
A''/A. Right?

00:07:48.250 --> 00:07:52.160
Just, put the A under
here, put the B under here.

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:53.470
Now what?

00:07:53.470 --> 00:07:58.390
This is neat, because
that function is only

00:07:58.390 --> 00:08:00.320
depending on time.

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:05.770
This function depends only on
x, so that the both sides have

00:08:05.770 --> 00:08:06.900
to be constant.

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:11.890
One can't actually change with
time, because this side is not

00:08:11.890 --> 00:08:13.410
changing with time.

00:08:13.410 --> 00:08:15.080
And this couldn't
actually change

00:08:15.080 --> 00:08:17.590
with x, because that's
not changing with x.

00:08:17.590 --> 00:08:20.030
So those are both constants.

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:23.810
So both constants.

00:08:23.810 --> 00:08:27.090
Let's see, I'll maybe
just put a constant.

00:08:27.090 --> 00:08:30.050
And various constants
are possible.

00:08:30.050 --> 00:08:32.670
OK, so now you see
the point here.

00:08:32.670 --> 00:08:35.580
Now I have two
separate equations,

00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:40.630
I have an equation for
the B part, dB/dt, B'.

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:45.920
If I bring the B up
there, I have equals,

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:50.330
the constant times B. And I
know the solution to that.

00:08:50.330 --> 00:08:55.730
B(t) is, as everybody
knows, what's

00:08:55.730 --> 00:08:59.180
the solution to a first order
constant coefficient equation?

00:08:59.180 --> 00:09:00.540
Just e^(ct)*B(0).

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:09.140
Good, we've got B. We've
got a B(t) that works,

00:09:09.140 --> 00:09:11.820
and now what's the
A that also works?

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:14.200
That has A''.

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:20.940
And I bring the A up, so now I
have A''=cA, so the A that goes

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:25.450
with it is?

00:09:25.450 --> 00:09:32.540
Oh, OK, I've used a c
there, so what's the good?

00:09:32.540 --> 00:09:35.970
I want-- Two derivatives
should bring down a c.

00:09:35.970 --> 00:09:42.100
Let me change c to
minus lambda squared.

00:09:42.100 --> 00:09:46.640
How about if I look ahead,
change this constant to minus

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:49.430
lambda squared, because
I want something

00:09:49.430 --> 00:09:52.840
where two derivatives bring
down minus lambda squared,

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:55.750
and what will do that?

00:09:55.750 --> 00:10:00.720
Any amount of
cos(lambda*x), right?

00:10:00.720 --> 00:10:03.530
Because two derivatives will
bring down a minus lambda

00:10:03.530 --> 00:10:04.230
squared.

00:10:04.230 --> 00:10:07.980
And any amount of sin(lambda*x).

00:10:07.980 --> 00:10:18.480
And this is now e to the
minus lambda squared t.

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:21.300
I'm doing this fast, but
actually it's totally simple.

00:10:21.300 --> 00:10:25.400
The conclusion is that I now
have a bunch of solutions

00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:28.880
of this special separated form.

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:33.470
Where B(t) could be that and
A(x) could be either of those

00:10:33.470 --> 00:10:35.690
or any combination of those.

00:10:35.690 --> 00:10:39.910
And I have to use the
same lambda for each,

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:46.110
so that the two equations will
work in the original problem.

00:10:46.110 --> 00:10:47.500
Good.

00:10:47.500 --> 00:10:51.080
Now, so far, no
boundary conditions.

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:54.650
What I've got so far is
just a lot of solutions.

00:10:54.650 --> 00:10:56.740
These times that.

00:10:56.740 --> 00:10:58.390
With any lambda.

00:10:58.390 --> 00:11:00.580
But of course the
boundary conditions

00:11:00.580 --> 00:11:03.060
will tell me the
lambdas, first of all.

00:11:03.060 --> 00:11:04.970
And how do they tell me?

00:11:04.970 --> 00:11:08.810
The only boundary condition
I have is this free stuff.

00:11:08.810 --> 00:11:14.640
So it's free, the slope should
be zero at pi, and zero at?

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:16.980
So that's the x direction.

00:11:16.980 --> 00:11:19.710
So that's going to tell
me-- I've forgotten.

00:11:19.710 --> 00:11:23.240
Do I want cosines or sines?

00:11:23.240 --> 00:11:24.640
Cosines.

00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:29.990
I want the derivative
to be zero at pi.

00:11:29.990 --> 00:11:32.910
Yeah, so I think I
want cosines, good.

00:11:32.910 --> 00:11:35.690
And then lambdas can't
be anything at all.

00:11:35.690 --> 00:11:41.570
Because, should lambda be an
integer or something like that?

00:11:41.570 --> 00:11:43.850
I think maybe lambda
should be an integer,

00:11:43.850 --> 00:11:47.090
because I want to plug in pi.

00:11:47.090 --> 00:11:50.560
So let me take the
second derivative.

00:11:50.560 --> 00:11:54.670
Is minus lambda
squared cos(lambda*x).

00:11:54.670 --> 00:11:58.910
And then I want to plug in x=pi.

00:11:58.910 --> 00:12:04.910
And I want this to be zero.

00:12:04.910 --> 00:12:10.010
So lambda should be an
integer, is that right?

00:12:10.010 --> 00:12:13.900
At multiples of pi, the
cosine is zero, yes.

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:15.270
Is it?

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:16.070
No.

00:12:16.070 --> 00:12:19.150
Did I want sine?

00:12:19.150 --> 00:12:23.800
Maybe I wanted sine.

00:12:23.800 --> 00:12:26.590
Oh, it's the first derivative
I'm looking at, thank you.

00:12:26.590 --> 00:12:27.300
Thank you.

00:12:27.300 --> 00:12:31.740
OK, good.

00:12:31.740 --> 00:12:33.580
OK, now I've got it.

00:12:33.580 --> 00:12:34.410
Thank you.

00:12:34.410 --> 00:12:37.120
And now I see lambda
should be an integer.

00:12:37.120 --> 00:12:41.090
Lambda should be, zero
is, yeah zero's alright.

00:12:41.090 --> 00:12:43.150
That's the constant
term, yeah, we need that.

00:12:43.150 --> 00:12:46.320
Zero, one, two, and so on.

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:51.480
So do you see that
I've now got, now I

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:53.860
can take-- I've got
a lot of solutions,

00:12:53.860 --> 00:12:55.510
and I have a linear problem.

00:12:55.510 --> 00:12:57.170
So I can take any combination.

00:12:57.170 --> 00:13:05.140
So finally I have final
solution is that u(x,t) is any

00:13:05.140 --> 00:13:12.690
combination, with coefficients
I'm free to choose, of A(x),

00:13:12.690 --> 00:13:18.570
which is cos(nx), because
lambda had to be an n.

00:13:18.570 --> 00:13:22.700
And n could be anywhere
from zero on up.

00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:31.070
Times e to the minus, lambda
is n, so that's n squared t.

00:13:31.070 --> 00:13:32.150
Did I get that?

00:13:32.150 --> 00:13:34.970
Let me draw a circle
and step back.

00:13:34.970 --> 00:13:35.620
What's up?

00:13:35.620 --> 00:13:37.380
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:37.380 --> 00:13:40.280
PROFESSOR STRANG: I
could have negative n's,

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:42.820
they wouldn't give me
anything new, right?

00:13:42.820 --> 00:13:47.510
I mean cos(nx) and
cos(-nx) are just,

00:13:47.510 --> 00:13:51.070
one's just the
negative of the other.

00:13:51.070 --> 00:13:53.040
So these are the good guys.

00:13:53.040 --> 00:13:58.360
I've got a cosine series because
I've got free n's, right.

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:00.570
Because of the
boundary conditions.

00:14:00.570 --> 00:14:01.300
Do you see that?

00:14:01.300 --> 00:14:04.970
That's pretty nice.

00:14:04.970 --> 00:14:07.770
There's my A(x),
there's my B(t),

00:14:07.770 --> 00:14:10.090
I can take any combination.

00:14:10.090 --> 00:14:11.600
Usual stuff.

00:14:11.600 --> 00:14:14.530
You get to that solution.

00:14:14.530 --> 00:14:18.950
OK, and now I have to meet
the initial conditions, right?

00:14:18.950 --> 00:14:20.990
Boundary conditions
are now built-in

00:14:20.990 --> 00:14:23.220
because I chose cosine.

00:14:23.220 --> 00:14:24.270
Or you did.

00:14:24.270 --> 00:14:30.810
Now, this will tell
me what the c's are.

00:14:30.810 --> 00:14:33.030
I'm going to set t=0.

00:14:33.030 --> 00:14:38.380
At t=0, I'm given the
initial condition, u(x,0),

00:14:38.380 --> 00:14:41.440
and I have the same
sum of c_n*cos(nx)*e^0.

00:14:45.460 --> 00:14:49.330
So this will tell me the c's
are the cosine coefficients

00:14:49.330 --> 00:14:51.850
of the given initial conditions.

00:14:51.850 --> 00:14:56.890
So I expand, so here's where
Fourier series has paid off.

00:14:56.890 --> 00:15:01.620
Expand the initial function
in a cosine series.

00:15:01.620 --> 00:15:04.550
And then go forward in time.

00:15:04.550 --> 00:15:06.360
This is just the
old e^(lambda*t).

00:15:10.130 --> 00:15:14.300
Only the lambda we're talking
about here is minus n squared.

00:15:14.300 --> 00:15:18.260
And you see what's
happening here?

00:15:18.260 --> 00:15:21.260
What's going to
happen for large time?

00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:23.780
So this is a very
physical problem.

00:15:23.780 --> 00:15:28.220
That I think you cannot take
18.085 without seeing this

00:15:28.220 --> 00:15:29.600
problem.

00:15:29.600 --> 00:15:31.430
You can't learn
about Fourier series

00:15:31.430 --> 00:15:36.410
without using it for
the initial value.

00:15:36.410 --> 00:15:41.610
And then propagating in time
with the usual exponentials

00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:43.150
for each one.

00:15:43.150 --> 00:15:46.690
And now as n increases
what do I see?

00:15:46.690 --> 00:15:48.710
Faster and faster decay.

00:15:48.710 --> 00:15:54.040
For large n, these are going
to zero extremely fast.

00:15:54.040 --> 00:16:00.090
So that what you see
with a solid bar, which

00:16:00.090 --> 00:16:07.830
starts with the temperature
u in some-- Oh, probably

00:16:07.830 --> 00:16:10.400
not negative unless
it's a really cold bar.

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:16.410
But, anyway, it starts with
some initial temperature.

00:16:16.410 --> 00:16:18.880
That flattens out fast.

00:16:18.880 --> 00:16:21.990
The heat flows, to equilibrate.

00:16:21.990 --> 00:16:26.010
What I approach is the
constant term, c_0.

00:16:26.010 --> 00:16:28.330
This approaches c_0.

00:16:28.330 --> 00:16:33.920
